extgreater}eff{\textless}sub/{\textgreater} = 1820 ± 240 K. Our new mass estimates range between {\textless}i{\textgreater}M{\textless}i/{\textgreater} = 11.9{\textless}sub{\textgreater}-0.8{\textless}sub/{\textgreater}{\textless}sup{\textgreater}+1.7{\textless}sup/{\textgreater} {\textless}i{\textgreater}M{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}Jup{\textless}sub/{\textgreater} (hot start) and {\textless}i{\textgreater}M{\textless}i/{\textgreater} = 14.0{\textless}sub{\textgreater}-0.5{\textless}sub/{\textgreater}{\textless}sup{\textgreater}+0.2{\textless}sup/{\textgreater} {\textless}i{\textgreater}M{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}Jup{\textless}sub/{\textgreater} (cold start). These limits take into account a possibly finite formation time, i.e., HD 106906 b is allowed to be 0−3 Myr younger than its host star. We exclude accretion onto HD 106906 b at rates {\textless}i{\textgreater}Ṁ{\textless}i/{\textgreater} {\textgreater} 4.8 × 10{\textless}sup{\textgreater}-10{\textless}sup/{\textgreater} {\textless}i{\textgreater}M{\textless}i/{\textgreater}{\textless}sub{\textgreater}Jup{\textless}sub/{\textgreater} yr{\textless}sup{\textgreater}-1{\textless}sup/{\textgreater} based on the fact that we observe no hydrogen (Paschen-{\textless}i{\textgreater}$\beta${\textless}i/{\textgreater}, Brackett-{\textless}i{\textgreater}$\gamma${\textless}i/{\textgreater}) emission. This is indicative of little or no circumplanetary gas. With our new observations, HD 106906 b is the planetary-mass object with one of the highest S/N spectra yet. We make the spectrum available for future comparison with data from existing and next-generation (e.g., ELT and JWST) spectrographs.},
